"An over-representation of factual presentations on how dangerous [global warming] is" is not the same thing as "an exaggeration of the dangers of global warming." In the first case, you&#39;re talking about which facts are pertinent, in the second case, you&#39;re not talking about facts at all.<br />
<br />
Think of it this way: we have a half-full/half-empty glass. I say I think its more important to talk about it being half-empty than half-full, because we need a completely full glass and there is a pitcher of water sitting right next to the glass. If I continually describe the glass as half-empty, I have over-represented this fact in comparison to the equally true fact that the glass is half-full. But this is not the same as saying the glass is three-fourths empty. <br><BR><font size=1>06:10 06-03-2006</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/vs/main/mpage.php?member=17798">boothwah™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">How was that taken out of context - <br />
